White's 2. Qg4 breaks the chess opening principle of not moving the queen out early, as the opponent will gain tempos by attacking the exposed queen. Not only that, it does not threaten [[Chess Opening Theory/1. e4/1...e5/2. Qh5/2...Nc6/3. Bc4/3...Nf6/4. Qxf7|Scholar's Mate]], unlike the other early queen attacks [[Chess Opening Theory/1. e4/1...e5/2. Qh5|Qh5]] and [[Chess Opening Theory/1. e4/1...e5/2. Qf3|Qf3]].

Black's best replies are 2...Nf6 or 2...d5, which both attack the queen and gain easy tempo. White might move the queen to g3, to keep an attack on e5 and g7.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.chesspublishing.com/content/1/mar23.htm |title=1 e4 e5 |last=Kosten |first=Tony |author-link=w:Anthony Kosten |date=March 2023 |website=Chess Publishing |publisher= |access-date=2025-11-23 |quote= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240527071404/https://www.chesspublishing.com/content/1/mar23.htm |archive-date=2024-05-27 |url-status=live}}</ref>

